></a></div><div class=3D"heateorSssClear"></div></div><div class=3D"heateor=
SssClear"></div><p>How much fabric do you need for a certain project? Many =
sewing patterns include yardage quantities, but what if your pattern doesn=
=E2=80=99t, or you want to hack or color-block your garment? Here=E2=80=99s=
 how to figure out how much fabric you need.</p>
<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp-image-26129" src=
=3D"https://blog.cashmerette.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/Cashmerette-cal=
culating-yardage-IG.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"1080" height=3D"1350"></p>
<p>(Want to sew your own <a href=3D"https://blog.cashmerette.com/2025/01/ca=
shmerette-club-meet-the-glover-jacket-the-club-pattern-for-january.html">Gl=
over Jean Jacket</a>, shown here on Jenny? Join <a href=3D"https://cashmere=
tte.com/club">Cashmerette Club</a> today!)</p>
<h2>Step 1: Make your plan</h2>
<p>Start with the technical illustration or croquis to plan out your design=
. If you=E2=80=99re color blocking, be sure to catalog exactly which pieces=
 you want in each color (use the pattern inventory to keep track). If you=
=E2=80=99re pattern hacking, make notes on which pattern pieces will need t=
o be altered and which you can use as-is.</p>
<p><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone wp-image-26117 size-full" src=
=3D"https://blog.cashmerette.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/Picture1-e17369=
53873950.png" alt=3D"" width=3D"899" height=3D"397"></p>
<p>(Want to plan your garment on a body model that looks like you? With <a =
href=3D"https://mybodymodel.com/">MyBodyModel</a>, you can sketch on a cust=
om croquis that=E2=80=99s made with your measurements!)</p>
<h2>Step 2: Gather your pieces</h2>
<p>Print or trace your pattern pieces in your size, making any alterations =
desired. Be sure to accurately transfer grainlines and other markings when =
tracing.</p>
<p>You will want to determine if you will cut in a single layer or on the f=
old as this will determine how many pattern pieces you need. If you are pla=
nning on cutting on the fold, you will only need the paper pattern pieces p=
rovided, but if you want to cut single layer for the most efficient use of =
fabric, you will need to modify your paper pattern pieces in the following =
ways:</p>
<ul>
<li>For pieces cut on the fold, make them into flat pieces by tracing a mir=
rored copy and taping the two pieces together.</li>
<li>For pattern pieces that need multiples cut, you can either trace off mu=
ltiple copies or carefully note the number of pieces needed and move the si=
ngle pattern piece as you do your layouts. (If it=E2=80=99s your first time=
 calculating your own yardage, we recommend tracking multiples!)</li>
</ul>
<p>Once you have all the paper pattern pieces traced out, cut them all out,=
 and, if color blocking, separate your pieces into piles based on the fabri=
c you=E2=80=99re using for each piece.</p>
<h2>Step 3: Figure out the width of your fabric</h2>
<p>To get the most accurate yardage results, you=E2=80=99ll need to figure =
out how wide your fabric is.</p>
<p>If you=E2=80=99re shopping online, most stores list the width of the fab=
ric, but you can contact them if they don=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p>What if you=E2=80=99re not sure yet which fabric you=E2=80=99re using? F=
abric is typically about 45=E2=80=9D (115 cm) wide for things like quilting=
 cottons and some shirtings and about 55=E2=80=9D (140 cm) wide for things =
like rayon challis and knits, but it can be quite variable. For that reason=
, we recommend choosing your fabrics before calculating the yardage.</p>
<h2>Step 4: Create your layout</h2>
<p>Next, we=E2=80=99re going to mock up our fabric layout; you=E2=80=99ll w=
ant to do this on the floor or a big table if you have one available.</p>
<p>Start by laying out a long strip of painter=E2=80=99s or masking tape on=
 the floor. Depending on the size of your pattern, you may need a few yards=
 worth of this tape. This is effectively going to be either the selvedge of=
 your fabric (if you=E2=80=99re laying out your pieces flat) or the folded =
edge of your fabric (if you=E2=80=99re cutting on the fold).</p>
<p>Using a large quilting ruler or a carpenter=E2=80=99s square to ensure y=
ou have a perfectly straight line, lay a second line of tape perpendicular =
to the first.</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp=
-image-26126" src=3D"https://blog.cashmerette.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/0=
1/Cashmerette-calculating-yardage-6.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"2105" height=3D"=
2000"></p>
<p>On the second line of tape, mark the width of your intended fabric, eith=
er folded for simplicity or unfolded for most efficient layout, minus an al=
lowance of 1=E2=80=9D (2.5 cm) for each selvedge. So, if your intended fabr=
ic is 55=E2=80=9D (140 cm) wide, your mark should either be 26.5=E2=80=9D (=
67.5 cm) away from the corner for folded fabric, or 53=E2=80=9D (135 cm) aw=
ay for unfolded fabric.</p>
<p>Add a third piece of tape parallel to the first to create the second edg=
e of your fabric. (Here we have markings at both 26.5=E2=80=9D (67.5 cm) fo=
r a folded layout and 53=E2=80=9D (135 cm) for a single layer layout.)</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp=
-image-26122" src=3D"https://blog.cashmerette.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/0=
1/Cashmerette-calculating-yardage-2-scaled.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"2560" hei=
ght=3D"1436"></p>
<p>Lay out all of the pieces for the given fabric, being careful to keep th=
e grainlines parallel to the first piece of tape (double check with your qu=
ilting ruler or a yardstick/meterstick). If your fabric has a nap or a shee=
n, be sure to lay all the pieces out in the same direction.</p>
<p>If you=E2=80=99re going to be pattern matching, you=E2=80=99ll need to a=
dd extra to your requirements to accommodate that.</p>
<p>Leave enough room between pieces that you can comfortably cut around the=
m. Double check that you have the correct number of copies of each piece an=
d the cut on fold pieces are mirrored if you=E2=80=99re laying it out flat.=
</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp=
-image-26121" src=3D"https://blog.cashmerette.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/0=
1/Cashmerette-calculating-yardage-1-scaled.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"2560" hei=
ght=3D"1777"></p>
<p>For folded fabric, you just need one paper pattern piece (unless otherwi=
se specified in the pattern). Any pattern pieces that are to be cut on the =
fold are placed along the fold line.</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp=
-image-26123" src=3D"https://blog.cashmerette.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/0=
1/Cashmerette-calculating-yardage-3-scaled.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"2560" hei=
ght=3D"1362"></p>
<p>For a single layer layout, you will need two (or however many is specifi=
ed in the pattern) of each pattern piece. The second pattern piece should b=
e mirrored (flipped over) and the two halves of the pattern piece that is s=
hown on the fold should be taped together down the fold line.</p>
<h2>Step 5: Calculate your yardage</h2>
<p>Measure along of the length of the tape to see how much fabric you=E2=80=
=99ll need for your layout. (We=E2=80=99ve added another piece of tape acro=
ss the top of the layout to make it easier to see). To accommodate shrinkag=
e, we usually add 10% to this measurement. So, in this case, we=E2=80=99ve =
measured 21=E2=80=9D (54 cm), so we=E2=80=99d want to purchase at least 23=
=E2=80=9D (62 cm) or 5/8 yard (0.6 m), or the closest available increment.<=
/p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp=
-image-26124" src=3D"https://blog.cashmerette.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/0=
1/Cashmerette-calculating-yardage-4-scaled.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"2560" hei=
ght=3D"1457"></p>
<p>Repeat this procedure to calculate your yardage steps for any additional=
 fabrics you=E2=80=99re using.</p>
<h2>Additional tips</h2>
<ul>
<li>If you=E2=80=99re color blocking with lots of fabrics, make yourself a =
table showing which piece is cut of which fabric. You can even write which =
fabric a piece should be right on the pattern piece. Keep a clear list of t=
he yardage for each fabric type.</li>
<li>When in doubt, buy a little extra! It=E2=80=99s never fun to be short b=
y a piece when you=E2=80=99ve done all this work.</li>
<li>You can also use this process if you are using a fabric of an unusual w=
idth and want to see how much you=E2=80=99ll need.</li>
<li>Make sure to snap a picture so that you remember how you laid out the p=
ieces when it comes time to cut them out.</li>
<li>Planning and sketching out pattern hacks and color blocking can be much=
 more fun on a body model that looks like yours! Create your own custom cro=
quis using your measurements with <a href=3D"https://mybodymodel.com/">MyBo=
dyModel</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp=
-image-26028" src=3D"https://blog.cashmerette.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/1=
2/Cashmerette-5107Glover-web-15.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"2000" height=3D"2500=
"></p>
<p>We hope this tutorial helped you calculate how much fabric you=E2=80=99l=
l need for your project! If you have any questions or your own tips to shar=
e, drop them in the comments below.</p>
